{
  "texts": [
    "Building on VQ-VAE [93], which introduced the concept of encoding continuous audio features into symbolic representations via a learned codebook, current mainstream methods for generating discrete tokens include self-supervised pretrained audio tokenizers such as HuBERT [24], and neural codec models such as EnCodec [58], [94].",
    "A general process involves first encoding raw audio into a sequence of latent representations, as in continuous sequence modeling: Z a = g(X a), whereZ a = [z 1, z 2,..., z T] with z t ∈ R d.Next, a quantization function q(•) is applied to obtain the final discrete audio tokens:u t = q(z t) with e ut = Q(z t).",
    "(2)Here, Q denotes the quantization function that maps continuous vectors to codebook vectors e ut ∈ R d, resulting in u t, the discrete token index from the vocabulary set.",
    "The final output is a sequence of discrete audio token indices: U = [u 1, u 2,..., u T].",
    "Specifically, self-supervised pretrained audio tokenizers, such as HuBERT, learn contextualized audio representations via masked prediction tasks and discretize intermediate features using k-means clustering.The resulting cluster indices serve as phoneme-like discrete tokens."
  ]
}